iii RADIO NEXT MONTH I
By PAUL NACHMAN
Grinnell‘s ten~watt FM radio
station will take to the air
"hopefully towards the end of
November," according to station manager Babak Arinajani.
“The radio station will be
amateur,” he said, “but it’ll be
better than what you can get
now. We'll be streaming clause<
cal music, serious jazz, and serious folk since the airlines are
pretty well separated with rock,"
The station explore 133 people—more than one-teeth of the
campus. Many or them are involved in an enormous amount
of behind-the-scenes operations
including engineering, patches<
ing, and program development.
“It’s an educational experience
for all of us," noted Armaiani,
a senior political science major,
“Few of us know much about
radio."
He arrested the educational
and creative outlets the station
will provide. “I expect there
will be something regarding
communications in the Curriculum Committee’s report. Mr.
I-livecam (a member of the
committee) is very excited
about the radio and has helped
us a lot," Annalani explained.
The staff has just finished
scheduling the 120 hour broadcast week. Morning \vakerup
programs, rock shows, newspaper, and delayed broadcasts
will be interspersed with the
more serious musical offerings.
”Delayed broadcasts" include
BBC transcripts of typical dis:
sessions, tapes of on—campus
gatherings such as the recent
Vietnam discussion in Gates. re<
holdings oi programs at Ex
Loco parental, and other gen.
oral features.
“Our news department is the‘
vendors,” Armajani said with'
enthusiasm, ”I think the 5&1],
may concentrate more On few<
turns once we get started since
we can get the break on any
campus story,
“We'll have excellent national
and international coverage—in
great depthaby taking full advantage of what the UPI wire
service provides."
The station has a fairly extent
site library of records and will
be able to draw on several private campus collections. An
RCA Red Seal classical library,
consisting of more than 140 record sets recently arrived unannounced, Armajanl noted—i!
complete gift, he added. other
record companies make regular
contributions.
The disc jackets for the rocks
shows will play their personal
preferences as to type of must!
on their programs. “Rock is de.
fixed in the greatest sense,“
Armaiani explained. ”We wan!
to encourage the deejays to use
