Editorial . . .
LEST WE FORGET . . .
Grinnell is residential. All but a few students live in the cold
legs's residence calls on the campus. Residence of students in
college is needed to create a sense of community, to emancipate
students from adolescent interests, to tree them from prejudices,
to foster independence, and to provide new experiences, perspeCs
lives, and limitations.
Grlluiell Is located ill a rural setting. Its location apart from
large population centers reduces instructions, promotes hard work,
encourages primary attention to studies. and favors participation
in the life of the campus. playing and execution of social activities depend to a large extent upon student leadership and initiative rather than commercial entertainment. Thus, the use of leisure time itself becomes a worthwhile educational experience.
Grinnell’s style at lite is simple. Social, cultural, and extracurricular activities flooring in number and variety on the Grinnell campus. Yet the style In which they are Conducted is simple
and interventions. Expensive hardcover, cars, and large amounts
of spending money are not necessary {or success in the student
society. In fact, there is no social identification among students.
and every social activity is open to all without charge, Grinnell
has no securities or transmitted, but the advantages of small-group
living are present in its unique residence system.
Grinnell is informal Ind flexible in policies and administration.
As a small college with an exceptionally able student body, the
college is able to experiment in education, to change and to adopt
readily. it explore flexibility in the organization of curriculum
and diversity in the methods oi instruction. All members of the
community, including students, participate in governing the community's affairs, which are conducted in a democratic and nonbureaucratic fashion,
Griunell is independent. As an independent college Grinneli is
I center of genuine intellectual freedom for both students and
teachers. relatively tree oi control from any outside source. in such
an atmosphere all members of the community have the opportunity —— and the responsibility —- to test the merit of ideas in the
light of truth, assured of respect (or their honest inquiry from all
other members of the community.
