‘ LETTERS TO
THE EDITOR
lliiiiiilliiiiiliiiiiiliiiiiilliiiilliiiiilIIIiiiiiltiiiililiiiiiniiiiiliiiiiitﬁ
To the Editor:
As I now conclude my sec«
and semester ot Humanities, I
believe that l have come to
some understanding of the pedagogical strategy with which
the small approaches the
course. Between lectures and
classes, dozens oi people have
come before me in an attempt
to get me to think originally
about the readings and to empathize with the characters
thereof.
I have concluded that the
more one is able to understand
and feel the experiences of a
literary character, the greater
will be the reader's appreciation of the Works It is in light
at this conclusion that 1 rec‘
ommend a minimum oi one
act of sexual interactive as a
pie-requiring for all students
taking Humanities lOl»lOZ.
How can a student fully appreciate the disability ot
Odysseus after seven years or
indulgence with Kalypso, ii the
reader himself has no more
than a textbook knowledge oi
their relationship? Can the passion of Dido be fully couple«
headed when the student can
claim to be no more than an
innocent alexander? Are not
the does of carlo and francisco automatically meaningless to
the uninitiated? And as for
gonna, well, let's be realistic,
I realize, of course, that the
above statements are not sufficient to warrant such a reads
