But all these odds are based upon it perfectly random deal
which. of course, you say. is impossible. That’s true, but a deck
is included to run “state" or “cold" rather than “warm”. The
manner in which cards are played in tricks, placed together and
“insufficiently shuffled" exhibits the possibility of random deals.
To solve that situation, you can try playing a couple hands of sell<
there, or dealing “goulash,” Le. dealing five to each player, five
again and then three. Generally speaking, though, the bridge
player is concerned to eat his stable of average hands, which
brings up a good point. Contract bridge is a game of mileage, The
better you do with the cards you get, the more miles to the salmon
in your game. Every bridge player over the long run will get about
ten points per hand, but some bridge players will score more
points.
